The paper deals with finding communities in social networks, which is a topic that falls under the intersection of computer science and sociology. The paper mentions assumptions about the underlying network, worst-case running time, and algorithms for recovering global structure. These are all topics that are commonly studied in sub-categories such as cs.SI (Social and Information Networks), cs.SD (Software Engineering), cs.DS (Data Structures and Algorithms), cs.SOC (Computational Social Science), and cs.LG (Machine Learning). Among these, cs.SI and cs.SOC are the most likely sub-categories as they are specifically focused on social networks and computational social science.
